import{c as t,Q as a,j as n,m as r}from"./chunks/framework.BXc4yaFE.js";const p=JSON.parse('{"title":"KV Caching in LLMs, Clearly Explained — @_avichawla","description":"","frontmatter":{"title":"KV Caching in LLMs, Clearly Explained — @_avichawla","author":"Avi Chawla（@_avichawla）","date":"2026-03-20T00:00:00.000Z","source":"https://x.com/_avichawla/status/2034902650534187503","type":"tweet"},"headers":[],"relativePath":"research/tweets/2026-03-20-@_avichawla-187503.md","filePath":"research/tweets/2026-03-20-@_avichawla-187503.md","lastUpdated":1779894392000}'),o={name:"research/tweets/2026-03-20-@_avichawla-187503.md"};function i(s,e,h,l,c,d){return a(),n("div",null,[...e[0]||(e[0]=[r('<h1 id="kv-caching-in-llms-clearly-explained-—-avichawla" tabindex="-1">KV Caching in LLMs, Clearly Explained — @_avichawla <a class="header-anchor" href="#kv-caching-in-llms-clearly-explained-—-avichawla" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;KV Caching in LLMs, Clearly Explained — @_avichawla&quot;">​</a></h1><p><strong>來源</strong>：<a href="https://x.com/_avichawla/status/2034902650534187503" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer">https://x.com/_avichawla/status/2034902650534187503</a><strong>作者</strong>：Avi Chawla（@_avichawla） <strong>發布日期</strong>：2026-03-20 <strong>收錄日期</strong>：2026-05-11 <strong>類型</strong>：Twitter Article <strong>統計</strong>：2161 likes · 335 retweets · 3968 bookmarks · 803293 views</p><hr><h2 id="全文" tabindex="-1">全文 <a class="header-anchor" href="#全文" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;全文&quot;">​</a></h2><p>You must have seen it every time you use ChatGPT or Claude that the first token takes noticeably longer to appear. Then the rest stream out almost instantly. Behind the scenes, it&#39;s a deliberate engineering decision called KV caching, and the purpose is to make LLM inference faster. Before we get into the technical details, here&#39;s a side-by-side comparison of LLM inference with and without KV caching: Now let&#39;s understand how it works, from first principles.</p><h2 id="part-1-how-llms-generate-tokens" tabindex="-1">Part 1: How LLMs generate tokens <a class="header-anchor" href="#part-1-how-llms-generate-tokens" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Part 1: How LLMs generate tokens&quot;">​</a></h2><p>The transformer processes all input tokens and produces a hidden state for each one. Those hidden states get projected into vocabulary space, producing logits (one score per word in the vocabulary). But only the logits from the last token matter. You sample from them, get the next token, append it to the input, and repeat. This is the key insight: to generate the next token, you only need the hidden state of the most recent token. Every other hidden state is an intermediate byproduct.</p><h2 id="part-2-what-attention-actually-computes" tabindex="-1">Part 2: What Attention actually computes <a class="header-anchor" href="#part-2-what-attention-actually-computes" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Part 2: What Attention actually computes&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Inside each transformer layer, every token gets three vectors: a query (Q), a key (K), and a value (V). Attention multiplies queries against keys for scores, then uses those scores to weight the values. Now focus on just the last token. The last row of QK^T uses:</p><ul><li>The query vector of the last token</li><li>All key vectors in the sequence</li></ul><p>The final attention output for that row uses:</p><ul><li>The same query vector</li><li>All key and value vectors</li></ul><p>So to compute the only hidden state we need, every attention layer requires Q from the latest token, and K and V from everything.</p><h2 id="part-3-the-redundancy-involved" tabindex="-1">Part 3: The redundancy involved <a class="header-anchor" href="#part-3-the-redundancy-involved" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Part 3: The redundancy involved&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Generating token 50 requires K and V vectors for tokens 1 through 50. Generating token 51 requires K and V vectors for tokens 1 through 51. The K and V vectors for tokens 1 through 49 were already computed. They haven&#39;t changed. Same inputs, same outputs. Yet the model recomputes them from scratch every step. That&#39;s O(n) redundant work per step. Over an entire generation, O(n²) wasted compute.</p><h2 id="part-4-the-fix" tabindex="-1">Part 4: The fix <a class="header-anchor" href="#part-4-the-fix" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Part 4: The fix&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Instead of recomputing all K and V vectors at every step, store them. For each new token:</p><ol><li>Compute Q, K, and V for only the newest token.</li><li>Append the new K and V to the cache.</li><li>Retrieve all previous K and V vectors from the cache.</li><li>Run attention using the new Q against the full cached K and V.</li></ol><p>That&#39;s KV caching. One new K and one new V per layer per step. Everything else comes from memory. The attention computation still scales with sequence length (you&#39;re attending over all keys and values). But the expensive projections to produce K and V happen only once per token, not once per step.</p><h2 id="part-5-time-to-first-token" tabindex="-1">Part 5: Time-to-First-Token <a class="header-anchor" href="#part-5-time-to-first-token" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Part 5: Time-to-First-Token&quot;">​</a></h2><p>Now you can see why the first token is slow. When you send a prompt, the model processes the entire input in one forward pass, computing and caching K and V vectors for every token. This is the prefill phase, and it&#39;s the most compute-intensive part of the request. Once the cache is warm, each subsequent token needs only a single forward pass with one token. That initial delay is called time-to-first-token (TTFT). Longer prompts mean longer prefills, which mean longer waits. Optimizing TTFT (chunked prefill, speculative decoding, prompt caching) is its own deep topic, but the dynamic is always the same: building the cache is expensive, reading from it is cheap.</p><h2 id="part-6-the-tradeoff" tabindex="-1">Part 6: The Tradeoff <a class="header-anchor" href="#part-6-the-tradeoff" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;Part 6: The Tradeoff&quot;">​</a></h2><p>KV caching trades compute for memory. Every layer stores K and V vectors for every token. For Qwen 2.5 72B (80 layers, 32K context, hidden dim 8192), the KV cache for a single request can consume several gigabytes of GPU memory. At hundreds of concurrent requests, it often exceeds the model weights themselves. This is why grouped-query attention (GQA) and multi-query attention (MQA) exist: share key/value heads across query heads, cut memory, and minimal quality loss. It&#39;s also why doubling context length is hard. Double the window, double the KV cache per request, fewer concurrent users. There is another idea called Paged attention, which solves this, and I talked about it here recently.</p><h2 id="tl-dr" tabindex="-1">tl;dr <a class="header-anchor" href="#tl-dr" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;tl;dr&quot;">​</a></h2><p>KV caching eliminates redundant computation during autoregressive generation. Previous tokens always produce the same K and V vectors, so you compute them once and store them. Each new token only needs its own Q, K, and V. Then, attention runs against the full cache. 5x speedup in practice. The cost is GPU memory, which becomes the binding constraint at scale. Every LLM serving stack (vLLM, TGI, TensorRT-LLM) builds on this idea.</p><hr><h2 id="研究摘要" tabindex="-1">研究摘要 <a class="header-anchor" href="#研究摘要" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;研究摘要&quot;">​</a></h2><p><strong>TL;DR</strong>：KV caching 透過儲存 Attention 的 K/V 向量消除 O(n²) 重複計算，換取 GPU 記憶體以達成 5x 推論加速。</p><h3 id="核心論點" tabindex="-1">核心論點 <a class="header-anchor" href="#核心論點" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;核心論點&quot;">​</a></h3><ul><li><strong>Autoregressive 生成的根本特性</strong>：每步只需最後一個 token 的 hidden state，但 attention 需要全序列的 K 和 V 向量，導致無 cache 時每步有 O(n) 冗餘計算，全局累積 O(n²)</li><li><strong>KV cache 機制</strong>：每步只對新 token 計算 Q/K/V，K 和 V 追加到 cache，attention 運算使用新 Q 搭配完整 cached K/V</li><li><strong>TTFT 瓶頸</strong>：首次 prefill 需一次性處理整個 prompt，建立 cache 是最昂貴的部分；後續生成每步僅需單次 forward pass</li><li><strong>記憶體代價</strong>：Qwen 2.5 72B（80 層，32K context）單請求 KV cache 可達數 GB，百並發時超過模型權重本身</li><li><strong>緩解技術</strong>：GQA（Grouped-Query Attention）和 MQA（Multi-Query Attention）共享 K/V heads 降低記憶體；PagedAttention 解決記憶體碎片</li></ul><h3 id="關鍵數據-工具" tabindex="-1">關鍵數據 / 工具 <a class="header-anchor" href="#關鍵數據-工具" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;關鍵數據 / 工具&quot;">​</a></h3><ul><li><strong>5x</strong> 實際推論加速</li><li><strong>O(n²)</strong> 無 KV cache 情況下的浪費計算量</li><li><strong>Qwen 2.5 72B</strong>：80 layers、32K context、hidden dim 8192，單請求 cache 數 GB</li><li>優化 TTFT 方法：chunked prefill、speculative decoding、prompt caching</li><li>主流 serving stack：<strong>vLLM、TGI、TensorRT-LLM</strong>，全部建立在 KV cache 之上</li><li><strong>GQA / MQA</strong>：降低 KV cache 記憶體，品質損失最小</li></ul><h3 id="批判性觀察" tabindex="-1">批判性觀察 <a class="header-anchor" href="#批判性觀察" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;批判性觀察&quot;">​</a></h3><ul><li><strong>無量化 benchmark</strong>：文章宣稱「5x speedup」但無具體測試設定（模型、序列長度、硬體），難以驗證或複現</li><li><strong>Attention 複雜度仍是 O(n)</strong>：KV cache 僅消除 K/V 重計算；attention score 計算仍隨序列長度線性增長，長 context 場景下 cache 效益有限</li><li><strong>PagedAttention 提及但未展開</strong>：文章點名後跳出，缺乏足夠引導；讀者需額外查找才能理解完整記憶體管理圖景</li></ul><hr><h2 id="評分" tabindex="-1">評分 <a class="header-anchor" href="#評分" aria-label="Permalink to &quot;評分&quot;">​</a></h2><table tabindex="0"><thead><tr><th>維度</th><th>分數</th><th>說明</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>A. Workspace 可行動性 (30%)</td><td>7/10</td><td>直接說明 prompt caching（Anthropic API 功能）的底層原理；可用於解釋為何 prefix caching 有助降低 TTFT，強化現有 <code>.claude/refs/prompt-caching-rules.md</code> 的背景知識</td></tr><tr><td>B. 創新性 (20%)</td><td>5/10</td><td>KV cache 是成熟技術，文章為優質教學但無新方法；從第一性原理切入是其最大亮點</td></tr><tr><td>C. 證據品質 (20%)</td><td>7/10</td><td>Qwen 2.5 72B 具體參數值和 O(n²) 推導具說服力，但「5x speedup」無 benchmark 來源</td></tr><tr><td>D. 技術深度 (15%)</td><td>8/10</td><td>從 Q/K/V 矩陣推導到 GQA/MQA/PagedAttention 完整鏈；不只說「是什麼」也說「為什麼」</td></tr><tr><td>E. 泛化性 (15%)</td><td>9/10</td><td>適用所有 Transformer 架構和 LLM serving stack，是底層基礎知識</td></tr><tr><td><strong>加權總分</strong></td><td><strong>7.05/10</strong></td><td>7×0.3 + 5×0.2 + 7×0.2 + 8×0.15 + 9×0.15 = 2.1+1.0+1.4+1.2+1.35</td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>整合決策</strong>：Rule <strong>理由</strong>：核心是通用原則（LLM inference 基礎機制），可補充到 <code>.claude/refs/prompt-caching-rules.md</code> 的背景說明，幫助理解 Anthropic prefix caching 為何能降低 TTFT。</p>',38)])])}const g=t(o,[["render",i]]);export{p as __pageData,g as default};
